hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the two-dimensional real plane, $\mathbb{R}^2$, which can be described by either Cartesian coordinates $(x, y)$ or polar coordinates $(r, \theta)$. The standard relationship between these two coordinate systems is given by $x = r\cos\theta$ and $y = r\sin\theta$.

Let $T$ be a type-(2,0) tensor field defined on $\mathbb{R}^2$. In the basis of partial derivatives associated with the Cartesian coordinate system, $\{\frac{\partial}{\partial x}, \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\}$, the components of $T$ are given as $T^{xx}=0$, $T^{yy}=0$, $T^{yx}=0$, and $T^{xy}=1$.

Your task is to find the components of this tensor field $T$ in the basis associated with the polar coordinate system, $\{\frac{\partial}{\partial r}, \frac{\partial}{\partial \theta}\}$. Express your answer as a 2x2 matrix containing the components in the form
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
T'^{rr} & T'^{r\theta} \\
T'^{\theta r} & T'^{\theta\theta}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
where each component is expressed as a function of $r$ and $\theta$.
